change_why: Students must maintain satisfactory grades and good standings with the high school as well as the college they go to in order learn responsibility and consequences. The income checks do nothing but confuse parents, counselors, and students. Do they have OKpromise or not. Some students struggle in high school and college when it comes to math and/or reading, they should not be penalized for their struggles. The $5000 increase did hurt many low income families that have excellent students that have very little means to send their child or children to college. Adding a cap to the number of credit hours that can be earned needs to be looked at more closely.  If those credit hours are needed to successfully complete the student's major or minor emphasis areas, those credits need to be paid for by OKpromise.  However, if students are taking just random courses, then these credit hours need to be monitored.
advertise_effect: I have class meeting with grades 7-10 twice a year.  During those times, I help students fill out a hard copy to take home so the parents can provide their information.  In some instances, I will mail that hard copy home.  During enrollment two days before school starts, I hand out brochures and applications and explain the program to the students and/or parents. At our open house, at the beginning of school, I hand out brochures and applications to parents.  Also, I repeat this during our two scheduled parent/teacher conferences.
student_help: I have a class meeting with grades 7-11 about eligibility requirements, academic requirements, and behavior requirements.  I go through every requirement with the students one by one. I explain to them what each on means and give examples of those requirements.  I check on each student's progress 3 to 4 times a year and let them know their academic standings.
burdens_4_text: The delinquency procedures are not clear.  Parents and students do not understand the meaning of a delinquent act.
overcome: I constantly go over the rules and guidelines.
parent_interact: My most common interactions with my parents are face to face, through their children, and by mail or the parent communication phone line.
difficult_case: I simply inform both parent and students what information they lack.  I give them the information how to correct the wrong/missing paperwork.
student_type: Most students get assistance in small group and/or individually by me. The students that need the most help are the students whose parents are difficult to work with in the time we have available.
rec: Parents and students need to completely understand the meaning of delinquent act. This is our biggest issue in our school.  Society has changed so much, children do not understand their actions have consequences.  Most of the time students/children do not experience the consequences because the parent bails them out of the delinquent act.

change_why: I believe if students cannot maintain a 2.5 GPA in high school in order to received funds for college that they should not receive those funds.  Putting a cap on the number of hours would allow for more students to receive the benefits.  Adding annual income checks would allow for a stoppage of aid for those who can afford it.  Since Oklahoma teachers and faculty are paid so poorly, if OK Promise was made possible for faculty members' children, more teachers would stay in Oklahoma.

change_why: Undocumented does not mean their parents are not paying taxes. Most of our undocumented students have really hard working parents who have found a way to support their kids in a country that allows their children to be safe where the country of birth did not. Some of these parents were swindled by people through thinking the social security number they received for work was from a legal means or process. Their purchased number allows tax money to go into our government system but does not allow tax returns to come out... These kids are caught in the middle of a political cross-fire. It angers me that this change was made.  The increase in income limits is a great asset to students and should be raised to keep up with costs of living allowances.
advertise_effect: Classroom presentations where the students discover what is on the page via a scavenger hunt type team project. I've found student interaction rather than the "sage-on-the-stage" approach is best.
student_help: Academic planning through scheduling of classes. Explanation to qualifiers of their responsibilities and requirements.
burdens_4_text: Fear of deportation
parent_interact: Questions of explanation of process post graduation.
difficult_case: We had a situation where a teacher required students to fill out paperwork in her classroom about 4 years ago. Students thought she mailed the applications in so they did not do anything when we continued to encourage deadlines to be met the next two years. We realized as seniors that nothing was originally filed... WHAT A MESS...
student_type: Those with parents who do not speak English or have never considered college for themselves or their kids need their hands held through the process. This is to be expected as it is new to everyone involved.
rec: A sheet that bullets the entire process from application to college graduation without all the extra words of explanation would be very helpful. In it the position for the person of contact at each point would be helpful as well.

change_why: I've been an educator for 50 years and here are my opinions:  Remedial work should be done in high school.  If a student takes the taxpayers' money, he/she should pass the coursework in order to continue--that's just common sense.  I don't believe the income checks while in college are justified--however, I don't know the legislature's rationale for doing so.  Once a kid is in college, don't put more roadblocks in their way.   Income cap should be at least $60,000 to capture more low income families.  I think Oklahoma citizens should receive the benefit of the tax dollars that go to OK Promise, although I know of undocumented students whose parents work and pay taxes to the US and to Oklahoma.  I see those 1040's when I enroll students in our college prep program. I think the current cap of 5 years or first bachelor's degree is fair. I'm not familiar with a limit of credit hours, but a student should not be able to change majors and use more OK Promise money than   a student who focuses on getting on with college.
tasks_7_text: I cannot officially do these things.  I work  with the students so they can be sure of meeting requirements.
advertise_strategy_8_text: Saturday seminars and small group meetings at schools.
advertise_effect: We use a powerpoint presentation during recruitment meetings and parent meetings where we compare the cost of college and common awards students can receive to pay for college.  The information comes from the current Counselors' Resource Book published by OSRHE. At each Saturday seminar, we include a 15 minute OK Promise student review of their individual transcripts and figuring their OK Promise GPA. We send letters to our sophomores' families who have not completed the enrollment.  We call and text parents.  I have made home visits just for that purpose.
student_help: We talk, talk, talk to them individually and in groups.  We teach them to analyze their transcripts and figure GPAs for college track courses.  They read the list of required courses from the flyer and compare their transcripts to that list each time a new transcript comes out.  School counselors are very helpful in sending us copies of the students' transcripts at the end of each semester, so we can work with students in a meaningful way.
burdens_4_text: Language on the application when it asks for financial information can be very confusing.  Also, they may not understand how confidential the documents are.
barrier_import_x4_text: Understanding the language of the application's financial requirements.
overcome: I have already addressed how we deal with student education.   With the parents, I sit down wherever I can meet them and go over the paper application one item at a time.  I show them their child's transcript and GPA so they can see proof of eligibility. Parents and students who have computer access still have to submit paper documents, so I offer them access to a copier and provide the OK Promise envelope and stamp to mail in the documents. I urge them to keep a copy of their submitted docs for further reference if needed.
barrier_9_text: Some school counselors do not have time to help students and parents.
parent_interact: We explain the program as a scholarship that their child can start earning right now.  We put a monetary value on it based on commonly attended colleges in our area.  We do this at parent meetings when students enroll in our college prep program.  We also call or meet with parents who have not enrolled their student in OK Promise.
difficult_case: When a parent refuses to release financial information, I tell the student he/she must concentrate on applying for other scholarships that do not require the information. This has happened to me 4 times.    .
student_type: Students who do not have access to computers or the internet at home are more likely to need help.
partnership: Our IHE partner is OSUIT.  We use their facilities for Saturday seminars and 5 week summer college sessions. We pay a small rental amount for use of meeting rooms on Saturdays.  OSUIT waives tuition for 10 students to take a 3 hour college credit class during the 5 week summer sessions.
rec: It would help if OK Promise could tap into the IRS tax form recovery system like the FAFSA does

change_why: I would still like to see the income limit raised a little more.  I have students who missed qualifying by less than $500 at my previous school.  I have only been in this school for 1 year as Guidance Counselor, and was out of counseling for the previous 3 years.  The changes that were made in 2017 were ones I had to check on to be sure I was up to date when I came in before school started. There have only been a few students who signed up in the past, and unfortunately I had several Seniors this year who didn't realize their deadline had passed.   The SAP policy is a good one for the most part. It prevents students from going to college just for the "fun" of it and emphasizes the importance of getting their education. I am a little mixed on the remedial course policy.  Sometimes their are students who are conscientious students, but may be weak in an area.  They will be successful, but it takes some extra help to get there. On the cap, my only concern is if a student switches majors and they are able to finish in the 5 years, but the cap prevents them from receiving the scholarship for their last few hours. I have not been able to find out what the cap is (I haven't call the OK Promise Office), just that it will be determined by the Regents this year. It may be set high enough that it isn't an issue. I can see why it should be in effect after a Bachelor's Degree.
advertise_effect: One-on-one and Parent Meetings
student_help: I am checking the credits  on a regular basis to be sure they are taking they are taking the correct courses, and trying to watch their GPA's to be sure they aren't dropping too low.
burdens_4_text: At this school, it is being sure they are informed, which apparently they have not been for the last several years.
overcome: I have tried to focus on getting information out to the students in parent meetings, in one-on-ones with students and/or parents, and  my sophomore mailing that I do in the spring of each year.
parent_interact: I go over the requirements and explain what documentation they need.
difficult_case: I have had situations in the past where the student had a parent who was incarcerated, another student who had a parent pass away, and other students where a parent had lost a job.  I have always been able to call the OK Promise office for help in these situations and they have been FANTASTIC. They have guided me in what information was needed and how to go about it.  I couldn't ask for any better.  I actually had to make a phone call yesterday on an unusual situation and was given exact details on how to handle it.  They are AWESOME!
student_type: In small schools, alot of the time it is the parents who approach me with questions regarding the application.

She was able to put her children through college, but it involved selling her house and moving into a tiny one in a different neighborhood so she could afford it.

change_why: Working as a counselor for over 20 years I am frustrated with OK Promise. I see many things that need to change. Across the state many of us express the same frustrations. There are many families who are claiming less because of farm deductions( multi million dollar land owners living in large new homes and new cars) and they qualify for OK Promise. Many, many of these..NOT RIGHT! Also those who have had tickets like DUI's or alcohol related tickets that eventually get worked off because of probation and community service but still get to keep OK  Promise. NOT RIGHT!  Have had some that have had trouble in high school and in college and get to continue on like nothing ever happened. We have many families that don't meet the income requirement so I feel the undocumented students need to work with the federal government to be cleared first. I think that OK Promise should NOT pay for the remedial courses, students have to have some buy in to be accountable just as there should be a credit limit taken.

change_why: In my experience, students who qualify often come from homes that neither parent has complete college therefore they usually have not had much parental support. BY not paying for remedial classes it leaves students, who are already at a disadvantage, with yet another obstacle (finances) to overcome. It is a small steps that sets them up for failure rather than success later down the line.   The additional income checks just creates more paperwork for everyone involved. As a counselor the biggest obstacle I face is making sure parents follow up with sending paperwork in. I am at a small rural school and able to help students and parents with this. Unfortunately for some students the best thing that can happen is for them to need nothing further from their parents once moving on to attend college. I just believe this is one extra step that sets our students up for failure. It is not necessary.

change_why: Many students simply do not test well and the ACT is not always an indication of college readiness.  While I think students should take the ACT several times and placement test, as well, I think remediation is necessary for some and by not covering those classes, the financial burden without credit will be a cause for many to not persist.

Remedial courses...as long as the state of OK continues to prioritize ridiculous testing, requiring teachers to spend class time preparing for the test, students will continue to miss out on relevant learning time. The ACT 5-year trend reports, beginning with the inception of the EOIs have shown a decline in the states' scores.  Undocumented students...we allow "them" to be in school; help them to assimilate to our society; provide the best possible education for "them"...but are not going to continue that after high school? I am Mexican. My parents came from Mexico. I have a compassion for anyone coming here for a better life. The only difference between now and the founding years of our country...most back then weren't brown. Income increase...even at $55,000, a family will struggle. I also feel that educators should be given tuition assistance for themselves and their direct dependents. Cap credits...I would need to know the pros and cons Good standing...why continue to spend money on a student that is not demonstrating a desire to succeed. Income checks...I really don't think this is fair. Some of the most hard-working families are not able to qualify, while some know exactly how to work the system to qualify. One specific example, farm [families], vice pres of a bank, 6 figure salary, files everything as a loss under farming...qualifies. A family earning 50,001 cannot qualify, being honest.

change_why: $55,000 is not enough income to afford college expenses.  By checking a student's family income throughout their college years is only adding my burden to students & their parents for the college tuition.  By eliminating payments for remedial courses discouraging students with lower testing skills to even attempt college. (This is from personal experience/ my son scored an 11 on his ACT all three times that he took it.  His first semester of college was all remedial classes & he was required to take  three more after that semester.  If OK Promise didn't pay for those, he would have had to get a student loan that would probably discouraged him from even going to college).

change_why: I agree with the income raise to $55,000 because that still catches the struggling middle class who need help to send their child to college. I agree that we should not be paying tuition for a student who is not maintaining satisfactory academic standing.  The student should place value on this scholarship and do the best they possibly can academically.  If they are not trying their hardest they do no deserve to receive the scholarship for that semester. I mainly agree that OK Promise should not cover remedial classes.  There's just a little part of me that is aware OK students have to be remediated too much so this will affect a lot of students who struggle financially anyway--making it harder to pay their college bill.  Overall though, I feel OK Promise probably shouldn't be paying for remedial classes (what we need to look at is why so many of our students need remediated--that's a whole other subject). Undocumented students should not be allowed to apply for OK Promise.  We can't provide support to those who aren't citizens.  We need to take care of our own first. I totally agree with the continuing income checks.  If a parent ends up making more than $100,000, they shouldn't expect OK Promise to pay for their child's tuition.  At that point, the parent should be solely responsible. As far as capping the number of hours, I am apparently not familiar with this change.
advertise_effect: Classroom discussions with students where fliers are distributed.  Followed by a mass mailing to parents describing the program  (I include a copy of the OK Promise flier).  With my sophomores who have not yet filled out the application, I start calling parents individually starting around the middle of May.  I keep following up with those that I know could qualify their child.  I follow up until the deadline date.  Because we are a smaller school I am able to have this one on one contact with parents.
student_help: Individual meeting with student each semester to see if they are on track to meeting the requirements.
overcome: Phone calls and letters to parents.  I tell them of my own personal experience with OK Promise and how I have had three children graduate from college using OK Promise, as well as having a senior who will enter college in the Fall (who is qualified for OK Promise).  Additionally I have an upcoming sophomore who is qualified for OK Promise.  I think my own personal story is persuasive in helping parents realize I have experience with the program and I'll bend over backwards to help them with the application process.  I tell parents to come to my office with their tax return and I will help them fill out the application.  I have had several parents take advantage of this.
parent_interact: Info. given at parent meeting.  Regular correspondence mailed to parents regarding the OK Promise program.
difficult_case: Many times.  Some parents are just unmotivated to complete the application.  I think a lot of times this is because the parent has a low expectation for their child (basically the parent has an ignorant attitude).  The parent doesn't have experience with higher education so they lack insight. Some of the difficulties applying have to do with divorce situations and families having to produce divorce decrees.  Or families having to produce child support papers or verification of social security benefits.  People can get overwhelmed thinking they have to contact the court house for a divorce decree or the social security office for income documentation.
student_type: Students in guardianship's or adoptions usually have questions.  Very academically smart students often ask for help because they have the insight to know that they want to go to college and need the financial help.  Student's who are not sure they want to go to college are the ones I have to really push to fill out the application.  Teenagers typically live for today so it's not easy to make them think about the future.  Filling out paperwork now for something in the future isn't exactly something they consider important.

change_why: I oppose the cap on credit hours because if a student is showing satisfactory progress and making the grade, I encourage them to take advantage of the program as much as possible - perhaps earning a double major or a major and a minor.  That is why I support limits to funding for students who do not show satisfactory progress.  Provided, of course, that they have a probationary period first.    I understand the reasoning behind limiting remedial courses, but sometimes students need those courses, and it's not always their fault.  Sometimes students simply are not great testers or need more time and support to master a skill or concept.  I do support raising the income limit for the program enrollment; in fact, I think that the limit should be even higher, as the cost to attend a regional university is so high.  It is honestly too costly for most middle-class families; I feel I'm qualified to speak on this, since I am a middle-class parent with a student who will be a senior next year.  I will probably accumulate more debt sending my kids to college than I did with my mortgage.  That is ridiculous!    I know some immigrant students, and, while I support them furthering their education, I do not particularly like the idea of funding it with my tax money.    I do support the income checks while students are in college.  I do not think families whose income is typically $100,000 a year or more annually should qualify.

change_why: I support the income increase because it allows more families/students to become eligible to receive the aid. I do not support non-payment for remedial courses because our schools do not have the resources to properly educate students.  That is why they are taking remedial courses in the first place.  If these students can't take a basic course due to monetary restrictions, then you basically have just prevented them from pursuing a degree in higher education.  I support an overall cap on credit hours, but not a semester cap.  I think students need to be aware of the time spent in college.  The national average is going on 6 years to graduate.  The more time in college, the more money spent.  A cap might help get them graduate in a decent amount of time.  I do not support annual income checks.  A one-time before you start is acceptable, but additional checks causes more issues for students and it should not be their fault that their parent's incomes increased.  That should be a benefit. I do not support no eligibility for undocumented students.  There are many who would like to go to college that can't because of no aid.  They already can't receive federal aid so any scholarship would help.  I do support academic progress.  It just makes sense.  If you don't make sufficient academic progress then why continue monetary support.

advertise_effect: I give each 8th, 9th and 10th grade student a paper copy of the application and encourage them to fill out as much as they can, then take it home to their parents for completion.  It makes it handy that the application has the envelope attached to it, so there's no question as to where it has to be sent.  Many of our students do not have access to computers or good internet service, so the paper applications are the best resource I have to make sure I make contact with each student and parent. change_why: I was a school counselor for 12 years before going into administration and have seen several changes to the Oklahoma's Promise program over the years.  I support the changes to not continuing to fund a students education if they fail to make or maintain educational progress.  As a parent who has paid to send two children to college - that was our rule as well.  If I am not going to waste my money, why would I want to waste the governments money (which is technically mine.)    In regards to undocumented students not being able to receive Oklahoma's Promise, I support that change - I know some students do not get to choose how they come to this country, but it should be allowed for those that have followed the process legally.  However, I believe we should allow undocumented student the opportunity to attend higher education - if they work hard enough, they can find a way to pay for it.  I struggled with the decision to to pay for remedial courses as I have seem many students who are just not good test takers - I can give you numerous student who are 4.0 students who have had to take remedial courses based on taking a test or tests.  One specific example that comes to mind is a valedictorian several years ago who could not get above a 18 total on her ACT - but graduated from OSU with a 3.6 in Business Communication.  She had to take remedial courses based on her test results.  Test results do not define who a student is or who they will become or limit what their potential is.   I can understand capping the number of credit hours the program will pay for, but we must understand we are asking 18 year olds to decide what they want to do for the rest of their life and they may need to explore a few options before they decide.  With that being said, we told our own children, we will pay for four years and four years only - anything above that and you are on your own.   I believe we need to set a limit and stick to it and not keep moving it - families of students that qualify one year and then the bar is moved the next do not understand and it is hard to explain to them.  I do not really agree with the additional income checks during college, I am okay with the ones during high school, but ones they are accepted into the program, I think they should stay.  I think you are setting students up to not finish if we "kick" them out of the program midway through college and they nor their family have had time to plan accordingly.

Our counselor meeting individually or in small groups with students at the end of the year to go over their credits and what they need to take to meet eligibility.

change_why: I do not believe tax money should go to illegal immigrants for college education.  I believe we give them more than we should already.  Academic standing - I believe they should make good grades but I also believe students can have difficulty adjusting to college and might need that taken into account.  Perhaps a probationary period if their grades were not up to standard before being kicked off the program. I do not believe the jump from 50 to 55K in income is helpful to very many applicants.  I would actually like to see the jump be to 60 or 65K.  Cap in college hours - the program is not designed for allowing double majors, etc.  Helping them get one degree/first degree is enough - in my opinion.  I don't think the additional income check is worth the time it would take for personnel to chase down all the paperwork. The second check at senior year should prevent those who can manage to just appear "low income" for one year due to business or farm "write-offs" as has been done in the past.  I don't believe any remedial courses should be paid for under this program but it is not something I feel strongly about.  There are times a student can maintain the grades needed in high school courses but have difficulty in a sub-test on the ACT - thus requiring remedial course work.

I think if they could show that they are in the process of being documented, then they should be included in OK Promise.  I think they should pay for a limit of two remedial classes, so that some students could get past that math hurdle. I would think math has the most remedial students.
role_4_text: As a Tulsa Tech Counselor, I'm an extension of the high schools and serve in a support role to the high school counselors and students. I try to check in with students that I know are on OK Promise, educate them on the requirements and promote our Success Center that provides evening on-line classes to help meet their goals.

rec: I would love to see the income limit continue to climb. These days $55,000 or even $100,000 doesn't go very far to raise a family, much less send children to college. There was talk of letting teacher's kids get on OK Promise,  and that would be awesome !!

change_why: I feel like the students will be held more accountable and we will not see as much of the dropping classes and not really trying on their ACT.  Remedial classes, to me, are out of place in college.  If they can't do the work in high school, what is one more easy class in college going to do for them?  I feel like it is just another way for the colleges to get money out of the students.  College is getting way too expensive and I do not see the need for it.
tasks_7_text: We send out a letter in May of every year to all students who have completed the 8th, 9th, and 10th grade informing them about Oklahoma's Promise and encouraging them to apply on-line or come to the school ad let me help them.
advertise_effect: The letter works pretty good, there is an insert which they are to send back to me telling me if they are over-income or if they have already applied or are going to apply.  On some students that I feel are eligible, I will call their parents and try to get them to come in or get a commitment from them to go on-line and fill out the application.   Some parents just do not want to spend the time or effort to do it and there is very little I can do with that.
student_help: I help them enroll every year and we have it on our enrollment sheets what they need to take every year in order to meet the OHLAP requirements.  Our graduation requirements align perfectly with OHLAP requirements.  Everything that is required by OHLAP is required by us plus seven more credits.
burdens_4_text: Finding their income tax returns and verifyng their income is a strain for some of them.  Legal guardianship is another.  Students live with relatives that are not their legal guardians, yet they are raising them.
overcome: I offer to help them apply on-line and I tell them what they will need to apply.
rank_7_text: I am a principal and a counselor and I do not really know which role I am fulfilling when I do all of the OHLAP requirements.
parent_interact: When they come to me for help with the application they are very appreciative.  These parents do want their students to go to college and try to better their situation.
difficult_case: Yes, I had a student that has lived with her grandmother most of her life--her mother was in and out of the picture and ended up in prison the last two years of her daughter's schooling.  The grandmother was not her legal guardian, her mother was.  I helped the grandmother fill out most of the enrollment form when the student was finishing her sophomore year.  I called her and told her she really needed to do this, she had ignored my letters the previous two years.  Her granddaughter was a very sharp student and needed to continue her education.  We finally got the legal documentation, provided by my superintendent, to get her grandmother in charge of her education and OHLAP accepted that and the fact that they did not file income tax returns because they had no income.  I was extremely pleased when OHLAP decided to accept her.
student_type: The students that are sharp enough to realize they need to go to college, yet understand that their parents are not going to do it and they need help with the application.
rec: I think OHLAP is a great program and they are headed in the right direction.  I like the changes they have made.  I might go one step further and say the students need to finance the first year and if their GPA is above a 2.5 at the end of the year, OHLAP will take over from there.  I have heard that New Mexico or one of our bordering states does it that way.

change_why: Students who qualify for a scholarship when they graduate should receive that scholarship regardless of whether their parents income increases - as is the case with most scholarships - because they are counting on that funding and cannot predict if their parents income will increase. Also, many students are no longer dependent upon their parents after high school and the parent income is not a reflection of their financial situation. I strongly oppose the elimination of eligibility for undocumented students if they would normally be protected under DACA since again, those students were not in control of their situation and do not have options available. The students who worked throughout school to maintain good grades and attendance should be rewarded for that effort if they meet the income qualifications. If there is a cap for the number of credit hours covered, it should at the very least cover the hours to equivalent to those need for a bachelor's degree with a minor.
advertise_effect: emails to parent and parent night forums
student_help: We meet with students annually to go over their credits and college plans, including OK Promise. For those students who have already signed up for OK Promise, we do a worksheet annually to check their progress toward those requirements. Those students with issues are encouraged to work on those things in the futures and are given information on how to remedy any deficiencies.
overcome: Meet with parents and students who wish for help in completing the process or who have complications in providing all the documentation, etc.
parent_interact: I most often meet with parents regarding GPA requirements and meeting both the core and overall GPA. I also often meet with parents just to do a check on progress toward requirements and any issues that could potentially prohibit the student from meeting all requirements.
difficult_case: Yes, I have had several students whose parents do not have the tax documents necessary or who are in the process of divorce and are unsure how to best proceed. I deal with these issues by calling the OK Promise office to get their advice on how best to help the parent and what is necessary to complete the process. My questions and the parents' concerns are usually answered quickly and easily. A few times, parents just weren't able to provide the appropriate documents and the student was not able to finish the application process.
student_type: The students most likely to ask for help are those who know they are borderline on meeting the GPA requirements and undocumented students who are unsure of how they will provide what is needed.

change_why: Putting a cap on a students ability to take courses does not help with the students ability to graduate on time. This also effects the students  6years of financial aid, which will cause issues with retention. I do believe income checks should be evaluated to make sure that everyone has a fair shot at receiving aid. Dealing with underrepresented populations, you will deal with a lot of students taking remedial courses. Why no help students who's school districts are failing by giving that student the chance to take remedial courses. This will indeed help those who are disadvantaged academically and economically. I support the income increase to 55,000 because it gives more families who were on the borderline to receive aid. I strongly disagree with withholding funds from students who are not in good standings. I believe their should be academic support/tutoring service evidence shown to Oklahoma City Promise in order for students to maintain college funding. I disagree with totally giving up on students.

change_why: We have an excellent student who recently had her OK Promise scholarship taken from her because she is a DACA student. This student deserves the money and her grades prove it. Now she is struggling to figure out how to afford college. This rule should be changed.  Students who have worked hard in high school and will need remedial courses in college are just as good candidates for the scholarship as students who worked hard and don't need the remedial courses. They may perhaps be even more deserving because their work at mastering the subject needs more time in college than others. The remedial courses aren't any less needed or worthy than non-remedial courses, especially in regards to having a scholarship pay for them.

change_why: Just as Tulsa Achieves does not pay for remedial courses I agree that Oklahoma's Promise shouldn't either.  A student should prepare themselves academically by taking college preparatory classes in high school and not easy classes to maintain a high GPA.  In addition I support the income checks to keep students from eligibility who may have a parent that takes a different job. That takes away from a student in need.  In addition I believe the same with the undocumented students.  Let's give them a way to become citizens legally and then make Oklahoma Promise a possibility.  But first let's take care of our own US citizens and help to support them.  I want to help everyone and I hate to see anyone go uneducated; but I do believe in order to receive federal funding or state funding you should be a citizen of the United States and be paying taxes into the system to help and support these Promises.

change_why: Most of the students these days do have to take at least one zero level course usually in math.  Most of the students I work with are first generation, low income and their families may not be able to understand why OK promise isn't covering a class that is required by the college.  I would limit the number of zero level courses paid for and only pay for them one time not repeat classes if they fail the course, not pay again if they failed it.  I think the annual income check will be a burden on those working in the Ok Promise office and could delay payments to schools.  They need more staff to help with that if they are going to add more work to their office.  The income increase was needed.  $55, 000 seems like a lot for OK salary but not if you are paying for kids and college.

They still contact me about what do I need to send it they are saying the application is incomplete.  Many say they don't have the time to fill it out even though it is a short application they get overwhelmed.  I have some that just feel like their child probably won't end up at college so why bother.  Which is sad because we encourage them to apply even if they aren't for sure what their future plans are because they can change.  Working with students and parents to build up a relationship.  Many times the students bring their paper applications back in to me because they can't put a stamp on it and get it mailed in, so I mail it for them.  Maybe having some postage paid envelopes.  I know online applications are becoming the trend but many of my students and parents do not have computer access or access to internet, especially in rural communities.  They are often confused when they are incomplete to why they are incomplete and we try to work with them on what they need to submit which is usually just income verification and spelled out on application but they seem to miss it or do not call Ok Promise directly ask our office instead.  Sometimes it is because they didn't go to college and don't understand the expense of college and why their student will need Ok Promise.
parent_interact: At events we host if the parents attend, or by mail.  I talk to them at schools sometimes when I see them at various events.
difficult_case: I have not, but there have been cases in our office where they had to contact OK Promise and spend lots of time on the phone trying to help those cases.
student_type: First Generation students need so much help.  Their parents don't understand the college process at all. Students that are not living with parents also need extra help.
partnership: We are a non profit so we work in various schools.
rec: There are some counselors that really try to get the program information out there and students signed up.  Then I have a school that doesn't really do much about getting the information to the students/parents.  Trying to get more students from schools with low numbers of students enrolled.  There needs to be another staff added to their program to help with the income verification.
